2 Training

2.1 Score for BMP Training Provided by Solidaridad

All farmers included in this tracking are farmers who have been trained by Solidaridad. At the first visit, the farmers were asked to rate the training provided by Solidaridad.

Reasons provided by farmers for the rating is indicated in the word cloud below

2.2 Other Training Over the Period

There is generally little training available for farmers to improve their business and farm practices.

3 Farm Characteristics

3.1 Tree Varieties

Usually farmers have more than one farm. The AEAs are tasked to gather data for specific farms, one that the farmers is really enthusiastic about. On the first visit to the farmers, the size of the farm as well as the oil palm variety on the farms are captured.

3.2 Farm Sizes

The farm sizes of the sampled farmers ranged from 0 to 4 with an average of 1.7 Hectares.

The farm sizes are categorized as less than 1 Ha, 1 to 3 Ha and greater than 3 Ha.

5.3 Use of Harvests

Sometimes the harvested FFBs are sold directly. At other times they are processed into CPO before selling. Some farmers do both at different times. The graph below presents the number of times farmers have either sold ffb direcly, processed or done both.

5.4 Palm oil per hectare - Based on farmersâ output

Palm oil per hectare is estimated under the assumption that all ffb from the farms are processed - 80% to artisanal mills (11% efficiency rate) and 20% to industrial mills (20% efficiency rate)

5.5 Palm oil per hectare - Based on farmersâ use of ffb

For farmers who use process their ffb, the palm oil produced per hectare is estimated. assuming 1 gallon is 22.5 litres(25) and 1 pigfeet is 56.25 litres(75). Use 11% extraction rate

6 Farm Gross Margins

6.1 Farm Costs

The total farm costs including labour for BMP implementation, harvests and application of inputs as well as costs of inputs is estimated and presented in the graph below

6.2 Farm Sales

The FFB sales, CPO sales and Total sales over the monitoring period are presented in the graph

6.3 Gross Margins - ROUGH ESTIMATE

Gross margin is estimated as the revenue less the variable costs. For this data, variable costs are labour costs and input costs as estimated above. It is worth noting that while some farmers process their ffbs from the farm, the total costs from harvests to processing was not captured in this data. A study from FAO in 2013 estimates an average of GH90 to process 1 Tone of palm kernel. This figure is adjusted with inflation using average CPIs in 2013(111.6) and in 2022(155.28) and estimated as 125.23.

The estimated average gross margins are shown in the graph below
